Jahrhunderts (Nendeln: Kraus Reprints, 1969), no. 3506), hand-colored in red, green and yellow, from an incunable German translation by Heinrich Steinhöwel of Giovanni Boccaccio's De mulieribus claris, printed by Johannes Zainer at Ulm ca. 1474 (cf. ISTC ib00720000). The work is dedicated by the translator Steinhöwel to Archduchess Eleanore. The leaves of this copy have been cropped at head and fore-edge margins with damage to the head of the border; see this image for a complete version. Green Co., was born in Chicago, Illinois, in 1893 and graduated from the University of Illinois in 1917 with a degree in mechanical engineering. He was a member of the Caxton Club from 1948 until his death and served two terms on the Club's Council. Greenhill was also a member of the Grolier Club. He died in Rhinelander, Wisconsin on 15 October 1968. Many of his books were bought by Bradley H. Martin and sold at Martin's sale. Greenhill's books are also found at Princeton University and at the Newberry Library. photo.description: Parchment binding of Philipp Eduard Fugger (initials P E F stamped on left board). Cf. Austrian National Library website. Philipp Edward belonged to the famous Fugger family of Augsburg, whose library was assembled by brothers Raimund, Georg and Georg's sons, Phillip Edward, Hans Jakob and Ulrich. Most of the collections of their library passed in 1655 into the present Austrian National Library in Vienna. A series of very beautiful copper etchings "Fuggerorum et Fuggerarum… imagines" was published in 1593 and 1618 in a small number of copies for use by the family members. One generation later the idea of the book of honour was thus again taken up in a topical fashion. The coloured print comprises images of 138 members of the family Fugger von der Lilie. Established heading: Fugger, Philipp Eduard,‏ ‎1546-1618‏ Penn Libraries call number: IC55 G7499 591d All images from this book

photo.description: Iesus saluator filius perducat nos superius vbi regnat in gloria Raynutius In Nomine Sancte et Indiuidue trinitatie [sic?] patris et filij et spiritussancti Amen Nouerint vniuersi [The first line comes from the hymn "Ave fuit prima salus". "Raynutius" may be a name (> "Rinucci"?) or refer to a chapter of canon law known by the name of one of the litigants in the case that gave rise to it. The sketch of three horses appearing above the trinitarian formula of the signum crucis might possibly refer to the passage in St. Augustine's work De Trinitate (book 7, chapter 3) where he uses three horses as an example in discussing the meaning of the word "person" as it refers to the Christian God. Or they could just be a sketch of three horses.] Penn Libraries call number: GC5 T2984 540a All images from this book

photo.description: At left: Staatsburgh N.Y. Apr. 25 1874 At right: Henry L. Ziegenfuss [Autograph of Henry Lafayette Ziegenfuss (1844-1894), who "was born at Kresgeville, Pennsylvania, November 3, 1844. "He was educated at the Moravian Seminary, Nazareth, Pennsylvania, and graduated from Pennsylvania College, Gettysburg, Pennsylvania, with honours in 1866. He was a member of the company of students enlisted in June and July, 1863, attached to the Twenty-sixth Pennsylvania Regiment, commanded by Colonel W.W. Jennings, which took part in the battle of Gettysburg. He studied theology at Mount Airy Theological Seminary, Philadelphia, and was ordained to the Lutheran ministry on Trinity Sunday, 1869. He became pastor of the Third Lutheran Church, Rhinebeck, New York. He also was professor chemistry in De Garmo Institute in that town. In 1872 his changed views of Apostolic Christianity and Church Polity led him to seek the ministry in this branch [Episcopalian] of the Church of Christ. He was made deacon by the Rt. Rev. Dr. Horatio Potter on October 17, 1873, in the Church of the Messiah, Rhinebeck, and placed in charge of St. Margaret's Church, Staatsburgh, New York. He was ordained priest April 20, 1874, in St. Paul's Church, Poughkeepsie, by the Rt. Rev. Dr. Potter. For six months, during the absence of the rector, he officiated at St. James's Church, Hyde Park. In the fall of 1874 he took charge of Christ Church while Dr. Cady was absent in Europe for the recovery of his health [and was elected rector on 1 November 1875]. Dr. Ziegenfuss was an acceptable preacher, and won the esteem of all by his geniality, and warmth of manner. He was an efficient aid in the missionary work of the diocese, and in May 1886, was appointed Archdeacon of Dutchess County." (The Correspondence of John Henry Hobart, v. 2 (New York: Privately printed, 1911), p. 394-395.) Ziegenfuss served as rector of Christ Church until his death. In 1890 he received an honorary S.T.D. (doctorate of theology) from Hobart College. His library contained over 3000 volumes. Cf. this brief biography.] Penn Libraries call number: GC5 St957 541g All images from this book
photo.title: Autograph of Henry Lafayette Ziegenfuss (1844-1894)

photo.description: Bookplate, identified in pencil ms. (not visible in image) as that of "William Jackson [of] Paris" (fl. 1865-1880?). According to M. McGatch, Jackson was "a pastor who resided in Paris and whose library was dispersed by the firm of Otto Harrassowitz, Leipzig, in 1910," adding in a footnote, "Jackson's nationality is unknown. George Lincoln Burr refers to him as 'the Paris pastor' with a 'rich Reformation collection'" (The Library of Leander Van Ess (New York: Bibliographical Society of America, 2007), p. 29). Harrassowitz's auction catalog describes this collection as "die Bibliothek des verstorbenen französischen Sammlers William Jackson in Paris, die etwa um die Mitte der sechziger Jahre des vorigen Jahrhunderts begonnen und von dem Sammler bis etwa 1880 mit ebenso intensivem Eifer wie feinsinnigem Verständnis ausgebaut wurde" (Bibliotheca theologica William Jackson (Leipzig: Harrassowitz, 1910), p. [iii]).* *Translation: the library of the deceased French collector William Jackson in Paris, which was begun about the middle of the sixties of the last century and developed until 1880 by the collector with as much intense zeal as sensitive understanding. Penn Libraries call number: GC5 St812l 529o All images from this book
photo.title: Bookplate of collector William Jackson of Paris (fl. 1865-1880?)
